Why Multithreading?
Better CPU utilization
Faster execution (parallel tasks)
Responsive UI (especially in apps)
Handles multiple users (server-side apps)

Ways to Create Threads in Java:

1. Using "extend" Thread class
class MyThread extends Thread {
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Thread running...");
    }
}
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        MyThread t = new MyThread();
        t.start(); // starts new thread
    }
}
2. using "Implements" on Runnable interface
class MyRunnable implements Runnable {
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Runnable thread...");
    }
}
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Thread t = new Thread(new MyRunnable());
        t.start();
    }
}
Runnable interface is preffered since its allows multiple inheritance and better design separation



Thread Life Cycle:
    New → Thread created
    Runnable → Ready to run
    Running → Executing
    Blocked/Waiting → Waiting for resource
    Terminated → Finished execution

methods in Thread:
  start() - start the thread
  run() - execute the code
  sleep(ms) - pause the thread
  join - wait for other thread
  yield - give chances to other
  interrupt()- stop/blocking signals

Callable vs runnable interface and furture
-----------------------------------------
Runnable Interface:
  no return statement
  no checked exception will be throw
  within thread
  When you call thread.start(), jvm runs run() method

Callable Interface:
  return objects
  can have checked exception 
  used with ExecutorService
  Callable is wrapped into FutureTask then  executed by thread pool 
      FutureTask<Integer> ft = new FutureTask<>(task);

Why Callable is better?
    Clean result handling
    Proper exception propagation
    Designed for concurrency APIs

Future Interface:
  stores results asynchronous computation
  Future<Integer> f = executor.submit(() -> 10);
  f.get();        // waits and returns result
  f.isDone();     // check completion
  f.cancel(true); // cancel task
  get() blocks until result is ready
  Future is not fully async because it blocks
Holds state:
        NEW
        RUNNING
        COMPLETED
        CANCELLED

Flow: Callable → wrapped into FutureTask → submitted to ExecutorService → returns Future

ExecutorService executor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(2);
Callable<Integer> task = () -> {
    Thread.sleep(1000);
    return 42;
};
Future<Integer> future = executor.submit(task);
System.out.println("Doing other work...");
Integer result = future.get(); // blocks
System.out.println(result);
executor.shutdown();

FutureTask:
  combines future and Runnable
Why important?
  Used internally by ExecutorService
  Gives control over execution
Problems with Future: 
  Blocking - future.get();
  No chaining - Cannot do: task1 ->task2 ->task3
Modern Solution → CompletableFuture (Non-blocking + chaining) 
  CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> 10)
      .thenApply(x -> x * 2)
      .thenAccept(System.out::println);

Can Runnable return value? Indirectly usinf Future Future<?> f = executor.submit(runnable);
Can Future be reused? No 
What happens if exception occurs in Future , future.get();  throws ExecutionException

