Runnable with Thread (Basic Thread Execution):
class MyRunnable implements Runnable {
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Runnable running by: " + Thread.currentThread().getName());
    }
}
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Thread t1 = new Thread(new MyRunnable());
        t1.start();
    }
}
main() creates thread -> start() → new thread created -> JVM calls run() -> No result returned

Runnable with ExecutorService:
ExecutorService executor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(2);
Runnable task = () -> {
    System.out.println("Runnable task executed by: " + Thread.currentThread().getName());
};
executor.submit(task);
executor.shutdown();
Task submitted to thread pool -> One thread picks it ->Executes run()

Callable with Future (Real Thread Execution):
import java.util.concurrent.*;
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        ExecutorService executor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(2);
        Callable<Integer> task = () -> {
            System.out.println("Callable running by: " + Thread.currentThread().getName());
            Thread.sleep(1000);
            return 50;
        };
        Future<Integer> future = executor.submit(task);
        System.out.println("Main thread doing other work...");
        Integer result = future.get(); // blocks here
        System.out.println("Result: " + result);
        executor.shutdown();
    }
}
submit(task) → wraps Callable into FutureTask
Thread pool picks task → executes call()
Result stored inside Future 
future.get() → waits until result ready

Runnable + Future:
Runnable doesn’t return result, but:
ExecutorService executor = Executors.newSingleThreadExecutor();
Runnable task = () -> {
    System.out.println("Runnable executed");
};
Future<?> future = executor.submit(task);
future.get(); // waits for completion
System.out.println("Done");
executor.shutdown();
Future<?> returns null But can track completion

FutureTask (Core Internal Working):
import java.util.concurrent.*;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        Callable<Integer> callable = () -> {
            return 100;
        };
        FutureTask<Integer> futureTask = new FutureTask<>(callable);
        Thread t = new Thread(futureTask);
        t.start();
        System.out.println("Result: " + futureTask.get());
    }
}
Callable → wrapped into FutureTask
Thread executes it
Result stored internally
get() retrieves result

